</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF81FFFDFF591B3187B1B3D4" blockId="22.[160,1156,316,479]" pageId="22" pageNumber="821">
This bright green dragonfly was very common, and we found it on St. Thomas at nearly every water body, lentic and lotic. Nymphs were always found in ponds, but adults were seen cruising ghuts, ponds (including ornamental ponds) and open fields. 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF81FFFDFC4A1B8C81D0B391" author="Donnelly N" box="[979,1156,385,410]" pageId="22" pageNumber="821" pagination="7 - 9" refId="ref24517" refString="Donnelly N. 2002. Odonata of St. Thomas and St. John, Virgin Islands. Argia. 14 (1): 7 - 9." type="journal article" year="2002">Donnelly (2002)</bibRefCitation>
consolidated records from St. Thomas and St. John. 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF81FFFDFD7F1BA9869DB3B6" author="Ramirez A &amp; Maldonado-Benitez N &amp; Mariani-Rios A &amp; Figueroa-Santiago J" box="[742,969,420,445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="821" pagination="9711" refId="ref28863" refString="Ramirez A, Maldonado-Benitez N, Mariani-Rios A, Figueroa-Santiago J. 2020. Dragonflies and damselflies (Odonata) from Puerto Rico: a checklist with notes on distribution and habitat. PeerJ. 8: e 9711. doi: 10.7717 / peerj. 9711." type="journal article" year="2020">Ram√≠rez et al. (2020)</bibRefCitation>
highlight this as one of the most abundant odonates in 
